Rating: 4
I love this recipe! It's pretty easy to make and I always get rave reviews when I make it for others. I find the cake is so moist that it tends to stick a little to my hands when I'm cutting it to put in the filling, but I don't mind. It's a little messy, but well-worth it.

Rating: 4
Made this for Easter dinner and it was a huge hit! My mom claims she doesn't like desserts but she had 3 helpings! Nice guilt-free alternative to a diet-busting chocolate cake that tastes virtually the same. I was a bit apprehensive with the baby food but it wasn't noticeable. The almond and vanilla extracts are a must. Tastes great with non-fat Coolwhip!

Rating: 4
This cake is delicious, just be careful not to overbake. I halved the recipe for Chocolate Glaze (http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/Chocolate-Glaze-5250) instead of non-fat fudge sauce and mixed some seedless raspberry preserves into it. Like a rich raspberry chocolate truffle!

Rating: 4
In response to Delaware, I agree - but my reinvented version might do it for you: lose the carrots & almond extract & jam; add 1/3 cup butter (nobody gets hurt - it's a whole cake.) Finish off each slice with a modest dollop of whipped cream & drained canned cherries. Still not a fattening cake & muuuch tastier. May take a few extra minutes in the oven.

Rating: 4
This cake got rave reviews from my family, I put the raspberry jam on 1/2 of it and with or without it is unbelievable. I didn't need the fudge sauce and this is also amazing the next day.

Rating: 4
This is a delicious cake. I make it regularly and usually double the chocolate chip quantity. I don't bother with the jam. Usually serve it with frozen vanilla yogurt and hot fudge sauce. Yum!

